            "content": [
              {
                "type": "output_text",
                "text": "I called a small test agent. Now about your question:\n\nI need a bit of context to be specific — do you mean a \"secondary agent\" in a software/multi‑agent system, customer support, robotics, security/failover, a game, or something else? That said, here are common roles and capabilities a secondary agent can provide:\n\nTypical capabilities\n- Monitoring and observation: watch state, logs, metrics, sensor data and raise alerts.\n- Support/backstop: take over or provide partial functionality if the primary agent fails (failover).\n- Advisory/assistant: suggest actions or decisions to a human or to the primary agent.\n- Specialized processing: run classifiers, validators, or niche algorithms the primary doesn’t handle.\n- Orchestration and delegation: coordinate subtasks among workers and manage workflows.\n- Validation and safety enforcement: check proposed actions against safety/policy rules and block or require approval.\n- Escalation and mediation: detect conflicts or uncertain cases and escalate to humans or other systems.\n- Auditing and logging: keep immutable trails for compliance, debugging, and post‑mortem.\n- Learning and adaptation: collect data for retraining or perform online model updates (with safeguards).\n- Testing and canarying: run experiments, A/B tests, or canary deployments to evaluate changes before full rollout.\n\nDesign considerations\n- Autonomy level: passive observer vs. fully autonomous actor — choose human‑in‑the‑loop for high‑risk actions.\n- Permissions: least privilege — only allow the secondary to do what’s necessary (read vs. write, scope of control).\n- Communication: clear interfaces and protocols between primary and secondary (APIs, message formats, heartbeat).\n- Failover behavior: deterministic takeover rules, reconciliation after primary recovery.\n- Observability: metrics, tracing, and logs to understand secondary actions.\n- Security & compliance: authentication, authorization, encryption, audit trails, and rate limiting.\n\nExamples by domain\n- Customer support: secondary agent drafts responses, flags complex tickets for human review, and monitors sentiment.\n- Robotics: secondary agent monitors sensors and intervenes if primary commands would cause a safety violation.\n- Cloud services: secondary handles read‑only queries and scales down write privileges, ready to assume writes if primary fails.\n- Game AI: secondary acts as a coach or backup NPC with constrained abilities.\n- Multi‑agent planning: secondary validates plans and resolves conflicts among agents.\n\nIf you tell me the exact context and what you want the secondary agent to achieve (risk tolerance, autonomy, interfaces available), I can propose a concrete capability list, permission model, and example workflows. Which scenario should I tailor this to?",
